original:
Nissan NCTC

2015-05-10
Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps under their current design should have separate listings for L3s so that status (like under repair) and alerts (like all stations in use and station has become available) make sense for real human EV users.    
                                                 Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are failing to be honest in several ways:

0. Many stations are out of order, but not listed as such on the advertising posters in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for under repair. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of order but still using the normally working icon.

1. They do not provide 30-minute free sessions.

2. They fail to time the sessions for you.

3. They fail to cut off the session at 30 minutes.

4. If you go over, they charge you $7. This requires you to leave work or whatever you are doing, exactly in time to cut it off. If you leave too early, then you cut your session short. If you leave right on time, you must still cut your session a little short to avoid going over the 30 minutes on your own timing.

5. They refuse to document or provide measures for when the timer starts and when it ends.

6. When touch screens do not work, you cannot use NCTC over app or telephone. They say you can dispute it later, but their dispute process is opaque and time consuming. That is not a free 30-minute charge, either.

7. What they should have done, and what they probably originally meant to do, is simply provide $7 fast charges for free to NCTC customers.
augmented: Nissan NCTC2015-05-10Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps in their current design should have separate listings for L3s, so status (as in repair) and alarms (as in all stations that are in use and station has become available) make sense for real human users of electric vehicles. Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are not honest in several respects: 0. Many stations are out of service, but not listed as such on the billboards in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for repairs. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of service, but still use the normally functioning tool.1. They do not offer 30-minute free sittings.2. They fail to schedule the sessions for you.3. They do not interrupt the session after 30 minutes.4. If you pass, they charge you $7. This requires you to stop work or whatever you do just in time to exit them.

original: Chargepoint does not set the rates. The station owner does, in this case the mall. Until recently it was illegal to charge by the kWh in IL unless you area a utility. That's why by-the-hr pricing has been so common. But regardless, $2/hr is not a fair markup, it is a major gouge. That's 6 times the going rate for electricity with a 3.3 kW charger, 3 times the rate with a 6.6 kW charger. I have personally spoken to mall management on this matter, and they are apathetic. And your math is off for the mileage. A 6.6 kW charger will get you ~22 mi. Still cheaper than gas, but just barely. Not so for a 3.3 kW charger.
augmented: Until recently, it was illegal to charge per kWh in IL unless you have a utility, which is why hourly rates are so common, but regardless: $2 an hour is not a fair premium, it's a big chunk. That's 6 times the current price of electricity with a 3.3 kW charger, 3 times the price of a 6.6 kW charger. I've personally spoken to the management of the malls about this, and they're unapologetic, and your math is done in terms of mileage. A 6.6 kW charger will take you about 22 miles. Even cheaper than gas, but scarce. Not so with a 3.3 kW charger.

original: TESLA OWNERS - MODEL S UPGRADE - They have a brand new cable, Model S adapter and the Tesla approved socket to plug it into. With 40 amps, charged my P85D at 25 mi/hr. I arrived at 1:30am after 16 hours of driving (and charging).  Dario, the night welcomer in chief was so gracious. He got out the brand new Tesla cable and adapter and then, with his cell phone light, got it plugged into the Castle & connected the car. Full charge this morning!  Plus charger is at back of one of the two handicap spaces right next to the front door.  You have to be a guest but there's really nowhere else to go once you drive up the long drive to the top of the hill. GREAT destination connection though, as dinner guests at Equus often linger up to 4 hours so that's 100 extra miles if you need it (or just top off) or a full charge every night if you're staying here.  The staff is helpful and knowledgable - really top notch. Come on MODEL S OWNERS lets lobby to get a couple of the 100amp home chargers in here like the places along the west coast that have MADE themselves destinations for Model S owners, convenient and comfortable for the only long distance, fast and fun, total EV made (just drove from OR to San Fransisco, to here, NYC, 4500 miles + in new P85D in less then two weeks - home to north of Boston tomorrow).  Thank you PlugShare members who added crucial extra info to charging locations - I couldn't have made it without you. If you want to travel north of Boston my home charger will be listed tomorrow, and welcome.
augmented: TESLA OWNERS - MODEL S UPGRADE - You have a brand new cable, Model S adapter and Tesla-approved outlet to connect to. I charged my P85D at 40 amps at 25 miles per hour. Dario, the senior night owl, was so gracious, he took out the brand new Tesla cable and adapter and then brought it into the lock with his cell phone light and connected the car. You have to be a guest, but there really is no other way to take the long drive up the hill. GREAT destination connection, although as a dinner guest at Equus you often stay up to 4 hours, so that's 100 extra miles if you need it (or just get one on top).

original: As a summer intern at Holman Cadillac in Mount Laurel, I've been looking for ways to improve our communication with clients about what it's like to own an EV, and to ease some of the common concerns potential buyers have. I tried to gain insight by taking the Cadillac ELR to all of the public charging stations in the local South Jersey area and judging the ease of use and abundance of stations over specific areas. This station had an affordable $5 nominal fee and was housed near the Chapel Ave side main entrance to the complex. Equipped with two spaces and two chargers, this station is within walking distance to the Cherry Hill Mall, Loews Movie Theater, and several other restaurants and attractions. www.holmancadillac.com

At an affordable price of $5, this station was located near the Chapel Ave side entrance. original: I stopped by this site to check it out, because it had been showing up as busy in the Chargepoint system for WEEKS.  Every time I looked it showed busy.  When I got there a Ford Fusion Energi was plugged in, and according to the EVSE it had been plugged in for nearly 10 hours, and was obviously fully charged.  As I was there the owner walked up to leave and said he and another local worker (with a Nissan Leaf) are tag teaming on the charger, so it will frequently indicate busy.  However if they are charged up you should be OK to unplug.  I gave him a printed copy of the *excellent* PlugInAmerica charging etiquette dashboard card ( http://www.pluginamerica.org/evcard ) so he can indicate to other EV arrivals that they can unplug him.  I also left some more cards at the station.
augmented: When I got there, a Ford Fusion Energi was hooked up, and according to EVSE, it had been hooked up for almost 10 hours and apparently fully charged. However, if they are charged, you should be fine to pull the plug off. original: Relaying another checkin from a friend ... With his Model S cord and the NEMA 14-50 receptacle, he found that his charging cable got quite hot.  Typically this is because of a bad wiring connection somewhere, and could be in the receptacle not the cord (with the excess heat then flowing from the receptacle to the cord through the wiring metal).  For that reason some Tesla Model S owners have been backing off the current draw, say down to 25 Amps.  He did that, overnight, and got a full charge.
augmented: With his Model S cable and NEMA 14-50 socket, he found that his charging cable was getting pretty hot. Typically, this is due to a poor wiring connection somewhere and could be in the socket, not the cable (where the excess heat then flows from the socket through the wiring metal to the cable), which is why some Tesla Model S owners have withdrawn the power, say to 25 amps. He did so overnight and got a full charge.

original: We attended the, "Odyssey of the Mind" event last Saturday. I had charged my Tesla up to 90% at the Double Tree hotel but needed a full range charge to comfortably get back to Buffalo. I had contacted Ms. Susan Crane, the Parking Services Director via email (scrane@binghamton.edu) about a week prior to the event and asked for access to the chargers in the ramp D parking garage. I was given an access code to input into the keypad of a specific charger. At the gate to the ramp the attendant had received a copy of the info needed to get me access and I connected without a problem. Later that evening, we returned home with 24 miles on the battery. Paid the $6 event parking fee. Charger was otherwise free. 30A@208V. Very shortly the issue will be less compelling since the Syracuse Supercharger should be online in a week.

At the gate to the ramp, the employee had received a copy of the information needed to access my chargers, and I connected without any problems. original:
I tested this new location out this weekend, and it worked out just fine.  I pulled in, they took my information and car key, and I hopped onto the waiting shuttle bus to the airport.  Upon my return a few days later, they brought the car out to me, all charged up.  I've posted photos here of the two chargers they have, one in valet covered parking and one in valet uncovered parking.

This is currently the only Level 2 charging near the airport, and the best place to head to in order to GUARANTEE that you will get a charge.  The other places nearby are Level 1 and you might not get a spot.  You pay a little more here but it may be worth it to you if you need a full charge to make it back home.

Note to admins:  when I added this location, I had been told that there were two dual-plug charging sites.  Each site actually has only one plug; please remove the extra plugs in this database record.
augmented: I tested this new location this weekend, and it worked perfectly. I moved in, they took my information and my car keys, and I got on the waiting shuttle bus to the airport. On my return, they brought the car out to me, all charged. I posted photos of the two chargers they have, one in valet parking and one in valet parking. This is currently the only Level 2 that is charged near the airport, and the best place to go to guarantee that you will receive a charge. The other locations nearby are Level 1 and you may not get a seat. You pay a little more here, but it may be worth it for you if you need a full charge to return home.Note to administrators: When I added this location, I was told that there were two dual plug charging stations. Each site actually has only one plug; please remove the additional plugs in this database record.

original:
I charge here nearly everyday during the week.  My office is just 1 mile away and during lunch I drive over and park/plug for 1 hour, usually gives me back about 30% points of charge, I know that I can drive from home and back on an 80% charge up each day, but sometimes when I need to run errands, I'll use these EVSE to charge up.

There are some people who park there ALL day and many times the cars will be charged up to set capacity, but the drivers do not return until either the next day or sometime well after business hours (8-5pm).  

Gwinnett Arena security has asked people not to park there overnight, and so far no problems charging.

original: An absolutely fabulous experience parking on Cannery Row in Monterey at the Clement hotel's new Chargepoint chargers. The entrance is on Wave Street, 1 block behind the Clement Intercontinental. The EVSE is free with the Chargepoint RFID card. The typical Level 2 J1772 and Level 1 door lock that will clear when authorized. When I pulled up to the ticket gate, the cashier immediately said "Up one level and to the right" It was so refreshing to have someone immediately point out where the charger was. There are two chargers in the corner with well marked spaces for EVs. The cords are clean, nice and long so you can head in if you like. Flat rate parking is $8. You can then walk out to the recreation trail or back out to wave street, however when you return, return to the pedestrian entrance on Wave street. You can use the cashier on the main floor or pay on exit with your credit card. EVSEs are not reserve-able, but you can check status on the Chargepoint website/app before you arrive.
augmented: The entrance is located on Wave Street, 1 block behind the Clement Intercontinental. EVSE is free with the Chargepoint RFID card. Typical Level 2 J1772 and Level 1 door lock that opens upon authorization. As I pulled up to the ticket counter, the cashier immediately said, "One level up and right." It was so refreshing that someone immediately showed where the charger was located. There are two chargers in the corner with well-marked electric vehicle parking spaces. The cables are clean, nice and long so you can get in if you want. Package parking costs $8. You can then go to the recovery trail or return to Wave Street, but on your return to the pedestrian entrance on Wave Street, you can use the cash register on the ground floor or pay at the exit with your credit card. EVSEs are not reservable, but you can check the status on the app prior to arrival.

original:
Very satisfied.  Good features:
1.  The CHAdeMO connector is easier to use than the ones I have used before.
2.  You get an option of having a text sent to your phone for a receipt and to let you know charging has started.
3.  Can use my debit card (just like a conventional gasoline pump) instead of having to carry a special RFID card.
4.  Nice bright screen at night (no idea how this works during the day, but I can say it certainly works well at night).
5.  Very clear simple push-button procedure.

original: Hi folks. We charged there on Saturday, October 5, and although the charging itself was successful, they booted our Nissan. There were no signs or warnings about the time limit that you can charge your car, or about the possibility of booting. So we filed a complaint with the Department of Consumer Affairs of NYC regarding they unlawful booting, in the absence of signs. Also, from DCA I found out that only towing companies are authorized to boot, the removal of the boot should be up to $25, paid in cash or credit, and the boot should be removed within 30 minutes from the time you paid the fine. They charged us $75 and demanded cash only. We are disputing this issue now and we'll let you know how it is going. Either way, it is illegal to be booted unless there are very obvious signs about that and the booting is done by a licensed company: http://www.nyc.gov/html/dca/downloads/pdf/booting_law_rules.pdf
augmented: Hello folks. We charged there on Saturday, October 5th, and although the charging itself was successful, they booted our Nissan. There were no signs or warnings about the time limit within which you can charge your car or the possibility of loading it. So we filed a complaint with the Department of Consumer Affairs of NYC for unlawful loading, as there was no sign of it. Also, I found out from the DCA that only towing companies are allowed to boot, the removal of the trunk should be up to $25, in cash or by credit, and the trunk should be removed within 30 minutes of the time you paid the fine. They charged us $75 and only demanded cash. We're arguing this issue now and we'll let you know how it works. Since EVs are real cars, used by real people with real jobs and real lives, it is not always possible to pause and move our EV the minute it is charged.  I think most of us would like to and try, but it often is simply not possible.

original:
Great spot for Solar Charge ....

The 100k array is laterally pumping electrons into your battery during the day.  
I paid for my first charge on the beginning  of my 210 mile return trip to Monterey.  I used the new SMUD (Sacramento) Fast SAE and Chademo.  They just charge 20 cents/kwh and still make 100% profit on the power. (about $2)  I was not required to join "Greenlots" but the guy on the phone was so nice I probably will since they seem about the same as Chargepoint and offer reasonable rates.  The security guard is very nice guy who "would not really notice" a non-employ in the L2 charge lot (20+ chargers/spots mostly empty!   There is also a L2 port at the east side of visitor lot but it is frequently used by EV employs for prime parking.
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

Other nearby Nissan Leaf dealer charge info below:

I recommend  Davis Nissan for a better sales/customer service experience.   They not only offer free Chademo but want to come out and chat EV and help you plug in.

Both Roseville Future and Elk Grove nissan must be some of the worst dealers in California.  I recommend a free L2 charge on these facilities and spreading the word about Davis Nissan.


Roseville Future and Elk Grove  Nissan dealer does not seem to want to promote EVs.  They have sold rights of the ChAdeMo fast charge over to  EVgo.  It will cost you about 10$ per 50% charge.  What a bummer for leaf buyers who bought from these dealers.  They also offer man "plans" like AT&T at even more cost such as the $15/month plan with $29 cancelation fee;-(((

Elk Grove :  There are also only 4 spaces for 5 charges.  I had to block the ChadeMO so I could do a free L2 charge.

The sales manger was not really interested in any of my comments for creating and supporting his leaf customers.  They did have all these "customer appreciation event" signs in the lobby.  I guess it must be more about training for manager;-)
augmented: I paid my first fee at the start of my 210-mile return trip to Monterey. I used the new SMUD (Sacramento) Fast SAE and Chademo. They charge only 20 cents / kWh and still make 100% profit on electricity. (about $2) I was not required to join "green lots," but the guy on the phone was so kind that I will probably appear as similar to Chargepoint and offer reasonable prices. The security guard is very nice and would "not really notice" that a non-employee in the L2 loading bay (20 + chargers / spots) is mostly empty! There is also an L2 port on the east side of the visitor booth, but it is often used by EV staff for first-class parking.

original:
Nissan NCTC

2015-05-10
Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps under their current design should have separate listings for L3s so that status (like under repair) and alerts (like all stations in use and station has become available) make sense for real human EV users.    
                                                 Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are failing to be honest in several ways:

0. Many stations are out of order, but not listed as such on the advertising posters in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for under repair. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of order but still using the normally working icon.

1. They do not provide 30-minute free sessions.

2. They fail to time the sessions for you.

3. They fail to cut off the session at 30 minutes.

4. If you go over, they charge you $7. This requires you to leave work or whatever you are doing, exactly in time to cut it off. If you leave too early, then you cut your session short. If you leave right on time, you must still cut your session a little short to avoid going over the 30 minutes on your own timing.

5. They refuse to document or provide measures for when the timer starts and when it ends.

6. When touch screens do not work, you cannot use NCTC over app or telephone. They say you can dispute it later, but their dispute process is opaque and time consuming. That is not a free 30-minute charge, either.

7. What they should have done, and what they probably originally meant to do, is simply provide $7 fast charges for free to NCTC customers.
augmented: Nissan NCTC2015-05-10Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps in their current design should have separate listings for L3s, so status (as in repair) and alarms (as in all stations that are in use and station has become available) make sense for real human users of electric vehicles. Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are not honest in several respects: 0. Many stations are out of service, but not listed as such on the billboards in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for repairs. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of service, but still use the normally functioning tool.1. They do not offer 30-minute free sittings.2. They fail to schedule the sessions for you.3. They do not interrupt the session after 30 minutes.4. If you pass, they charge you $7. This requires you to stop work or whatever you do just in time to exit them.

original:
This is my first time at a ChargePoint station. I just got the car--in fact it's my first charge. 

Smarter EV owners would know to learn about chargepoint prior to driving to one with only 9 miles of charge left. 

I parked, the unit was locked--meaning it needed the card to activate it. I don't have a card, so I went in the the Marriott to ask for one. 

They couldn't find it. After about 5 minutes I gave up and decided to crawl over to Amerigreen or the Hampton. 

But on a whim I called Chargepoint and learned they can unlock it from afar over the interwebs. This internet thing is going to be big. 

You can also unlock it from their app, but there's no mention of that at the app store. Important safety tip, Egon. 

They got me going and it's charging now. 

The Marriott staff were very friendly and accommodating--they just didn't know (like me) how it worked. I impressed upon them the importance of the staff knowing, and having a card handy. 

It worked out nicely--I'm sitting in their lobby cafe, about to work for an hour over coffee and eggs. Not farm fresh, free-range organic eggs, but it's a meal. :)
augmented: This is my first time at a ChargePoint station. I just got the car - in fact, it's my first charge. Smart EV owners would know how to find a charging point before driving to one with only 9 miles of charge left. I parked, the device was locked - that is, it needed the card to activate it. I don't have a card, so I went to the Marriott to ask for one. They couldn't find it. After about 5 minutes I gave up and decided to crawl to Amerigreen or Hampton. But on a whim I called Chargepoint and learned that they can unlock it remotely via the web. This Internet thing will be great. You can also unlock it from their app, but there's no question about that in the app store. Important safety tip, Egon. They got me going and it's charging now. The Marriott staff were very friendly and courteous - they just didn't know (how I did) how it worked.

original:
Charged at 120 Volts on a conventional outlet (see picture of blue Leaf) for about 1/2 hour while I talked with the owner of the B&B.  They are welcoming to EV drivers using their 120 Volt and NEMA 14-50 240 Volt sockets, though they are not EV drivers themselves.  The charging is I think pretty much intended for guests, though the owner said also that a non-guest driving through is welcome to use the charging at this point (this writing is as of 2015-02-08).  I suggest to fellow EV drivers to make a good effort to be polite and express gratitude for use of the charging since there are very few public stations around this area.  The owner may at some point install J1772 or similar, but at this point it is just 120 Volt and NEMA 14-50.  The plugshare entry indicates some sort of Tesla plug, but I think they are just referring to the NEMA 14-50.

Location: the plugs are one or two structures to the North of the entrance of the B&B (that is part of what I was trying to show with thepictures I uploaded.  The NEMA 14-50 is painted red and is a very small dot in one of the pictures.
augmented: Charged at 120 volts on a conventional outlet (see picture of the blue Leaf) for about 1 / 2 hours while I was talking to the owner of the B & B., electric vehicle drivers who use their 120 volts and NEMA 14-50 240 volt outlets, even though they are not electric drivers themselves, are welcome. The charging is, in my opinion, more for guests, although the owner also said that a non-guest who drives through is welcome to use the charging at this point (this inscription dates from 2015-02-08).I suggest that other electric drivers make an effort to be polite and express gratitude for using the charging, as there are very few public stations in this area.The owner may sometime install J1772 or similar, but at this point it is only 120 volts and NEMA 14-50. The plug-share entry indicates some kind of Tesla plug, but I think they refer only to the NEMA-14 connectors, which are a very north B or two structures.

Metro should have installed many L1 outlets to accompany the L2 so people can top off via L2 at the end of the day & use L1 during the day.
augmented: Tom, it's a subway station: people travel many miles to get there, get on the train and take the train to work or to a far away place. I want the subway to change the signage so that it reflects the real purpose of the lot, which is to allow daily commuters with electric vehicles to have a recharged car on the way back from their trip. Subway should have set up many L1 outlets to accompany the L2 so that people can lock up on the L2 at the end of the day and use L1 during the day.

original:
Worked great!
For some odd reason, the Chargepoint app was showing that one of the two chargers was in use, when in fact NEITHER was in use. After I plugged in, it showed that BOTH were in use. Must be a bug.

The grocery store has a deli with hot food and sushi, and it's a grocery store, so you can get pretty much anything you want (cold drinks, coffee, etc.)

The deli area has some tables and chairs to sit and eat at, and also has free WiFi. There was a picnic table and shade umbrella outside as well.

If you get some food "to go", do yourself a favor and walk one country block west to Tyranea Park. It's a little wooded park with plenty of picnic tables and access to Rock Lake. I sat down by the lake and ate lunch. When I got back to my electric motorcycle, it was fully charged.

Because this is a ChargePoint station, using the app on your smartphone, you can check your rate of charge, if you are done charging, etc. It's pretty handy.
augmented: For some strange reason, the ChargePoint app showed that one of the two chargers was in use, although actually NEITER was in use. After I connected, it showed that BOTH were in use. Must be a bug. The grocery store has a deli with hot food and sushi, and it's also a grocery store so you can get pretty much anything you want (cold drinks, coffee, etc.) The deli area has some tables and chairs to sit and eat and also has free WiFi. There was also a picnic table and an umbrella outside. When you get something to eat "to go," do yourself a favor and walk a land block west to Tyranea Park. It's a small wooded park with lots of picnic tables and access to Rock Lake. I sat by the lake and had lunch. When I got back to my electric motorcycle, it was fully charged. As this is a ChargePoint station, with the app on your smartphone, you can check your charging rate.

original: To those whom use these stations, please help us, the ev community. Only charge for as long as you need to to get home, and plug in at home as well, don't abuse the chargers, others need them as well. Also, please leave a note on your vehicle, or on PlugShare, about if and when it would be acceptable to unplug your vehicle if you are not around and/or contact information to inquire. If your car is equipped with an unplug alarm, and you can't be contacted, please disable the alarm. To the Tesla specifically, I've notice you parked and plugged in day after day for hours and hours. Unless you have a VERY long drive to campus, I would have to assume you're abusing the system by not plugging in at home. Either way, please help the community in one of a few ways. A Tesla supercharger is located a few miles away, please use that if you need a lot of power. Also, your car has a ChaDeMo option, please invest in that option and use the fast charger. Many cars don't have a fast charge option, so a lengthy use of that would, in most cases, be ideal. Also, when your car is done charging, please move your car as soon as possible. To anyone who lives on campus, please refrain from using the chargers during the day which is when commuters may need them, a overnight charge is almost always perfectly fine.
augmented: For those who use these stations, please help us, the community of ChaDeMo. Only charge for as long as you need to go home, and connect your vehicle to your home, do not abuse the chargers, others need them as well. Please leave a note on your vehicle or on PlugShare if and when it would be acceptable to disconnect your vehicle if you are not nearby and / or need contact information to check. If your car is equipped with a disconnect alarm and you cannot be connected to your home, please disable the alarm. Specifically, to the Tesla I noticed that you are parked and connected for hours every day. Unless you have a VERY long drive to campus, I would assume that you are abusing the system by not connecting to your home. In any case, please help the community in one of a few ways. A Tesla supercharger is located a few miles away, please use this if you need a lot of power.

Many people that have electric cars do not have places to charge at thier home, as they live in multi family places, they may not even have an off street parking spot.. and even if they have off street parking may not be allowe or have control of installing a home charger in an apartment building parking lot. And besides that, there are many other places near by, if you are in need of emergency electricity.. And if you are in a hybrid plug in electric is very wrong to unplug a full electric car which does not have the facilities you have to just run up to a gas station and refuel in under a minute at thousands of places around town. Please be considerate of others in the community. If you have issue with this, please state your views for discussion with the rest of us to explore this important topic.
augmented: If the person who has done this is reading this, and so are others. If a car is being charged, please do not take your car off. And even if they do have off-street parking, they may not be allowed or have control over installing a charger in an apartment parking lot. Plus, there are many other places nearby if you need emergency power. And, if you are in a hybrid vehicle with power, it is completely wrong to unplug an all-electric car that does not have the facilities you need to just walk to a gas station and refuel in less than a minute at thousands of locations in the city. Please be considerate with others in the community. If you have problems with this, please share your views for a discussion with the rest of us to explore this important issue.

original:
On the 28th, I successfully charged using the working (left) charger for almost a half hour.  On the 29th, the same one stopped after 10 minutes.  I called Blink to explain and they were able to start the right side remotely (as a one-time "favor") to allow me to finish my charge.  (The broken screen only prevents drivers from using it!)

The rep said it was a one-time only favor and that essentially I should wait until they were fixed before relying on them again.  When I asked how I'd know without going there, he had no advice.  Great.  I hope it is soon (and that they develop a notification system as eVgo appears to have).

So until then, you're taking a risk coming here: the left side might stop prematurely, and you will only get one "grace" charge from the right side.

original: I think a lot of Leaf drivers don't realize that quick charging above 80% isn't quick charging. Below about 60% you charge at about 120amps it begins tapering. The charger drops the supplied amps very sharply. You probably charge just as fast on Level2 above around 90%. I waited while a guy charged well above 95%. It was charging at a paltry 9 amps. I flagged the guy and said "you're charging at 9 amps, it will take like 15 minutes to finish that last couple percent" he seemed angry and said "You're kicking me out? Just take the charger." I feel like a jerk but he was wasting both of our time. Just thought I'd give a PSA.
augmented: I think a lot of Leaf drivers don't realize that fast charging over 80% is not fast charging. Below about 60% you charge at about 120 Amps, it tapers off. The charger drops the delivered Amps very steeply. They probably charge just as fast at Level 2 over about 90%. I waited while a guy charges at well over 95%. It charges at a paltry 9 Amps. I showed the guy and said, "You charge at 9 Amps, it takes 15 minutes to complete the last few percent," he seemed angry and said, "You throw me out? Just take the charger." I feel like a jerk, but he's wasting our time. I just thought I'd give a PSA.

original: Fiat was wrong to unplug the Volt. Volt is same concept as BMW i3 Rexx, a range extended electric vehicle (EREV) . Volt has 44 miles range usually  ( 55-60 in new model) with an electric generator powered by gasoline engine which is active when the battery is considered depleted. A driver can fully accelerate a volt to top speed and the gasoline generator will not turn on as long as battery is not empty. A plug-in hybrid would require help from a gasoline powered engine to accelerate under those conditions and many less demanding conditions.
augmented: Fiat was wrong to turn off the Volt. Volt is the same concept as the BMW i3 Rexx, an extended-range electric vehicle (EREV). Normally, the Volt has a range of 44 miles (55-60 in new models) with an electric generator powered by a gasoline engine that is active when the battery is deemed to be exhausted. A driver can accelerate one Volt fully to top speed and the gasoline generator does not turn on until the battery is empty. A plug-in hybrid would require the help of a gasoline engine to accelerate in these conditions and many less demanding conditions.

original: "Cost" field references a Level 3 charger. There is no such thing as a Level 3 charger. There are Level 3 chargers in Europe but this station is not in Europe. The normal 240V EV charger is based on the SAE J1772 AC Level 2 standard. There is a SAE J1772 AC Level 3 standard but it's a 240V, 3 phase standard that has not been adopted by any auto manufacturer in the United States. The CCS chargers common at many charging stations are based on the SAE J1772 DC Level 2 standard. The CHAdeMO chargers are not based on the SAE J1772 standard and therefore the level designations do not apply.
augmented: "Cost" refers to a Level 3 charger. There is no Level 3 charger. There are Level 3 chargers in Europe, but this station is not located in Europe. The normal 240V charger is based on the AC Level 2 standard SAE J1772. There is an AC Level 3 standard SAE J1772, but it is a 240V 3-phase standard that has not been adopted by any automaker in the U.S. The CCS chargers common at many charging stations are based on the DC Level 2 standard SAE J1772. CHAdeMO chargers are not based on the SAE J1772 standard and therefore the level designations do not apply.

Great spot for Solar Charge ....

The 100k array is laterally pumping electrons into your battery during the day.

They just charge 20 cents/kwh and still make 100% profit on the power. (about $2)  I was not required to join "Greenlots" but the guy on the phone was so nice I probably will since they seem about the same as Chargepoint and offer reasonable rates.  The security guard is very nice guy who "would not really notice" a non-employ in the L2 charge lot (20+ chargers/spots mostly empty!   There is also a L2 port at the east side of visitor lot but it is frequently used by EV employs for prime parking.
xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxx

Other nearby Nissan Leaf dealer charge info below:

I recommend  Davis Nissan for a better sales/customer service experience.   They not only offer free Chademo but want to come out and chat EV and help you plug in.

Both Roseville Future and Elk Grove nissan must be some of the worst dealers in California.  I recommend a free L2 charge on these facilities and spreading the word about Davis Nissan.


Roseville Future and Elk Grove  Nissan dealer does not seem to want to promote EVs.  They have sold rights of the ChAdeMo fast charge over to  EVgo.  It will cost you about 10$ per 50% charge.  What a bummer for leaf buyers who bought from these dealers.  They also offer man "plans" like AT&T at even more cost such as the $15/month plan with $29 cancelation fee;-(((

Elk Grove :  There are also only 4 spaces for 5 charges.  I had to block the ChadeMO so I could do a free L2 charge.

The sales manger was not really interested in any of my comments for creating and supporting his leaf customers.  They did have all these "customer appreciation event" signs in the lobby.  I guess it must be more about training for manager;-)
augmented: I paid my first fee at the start of my 210-mile return trip to Monterey. I used the new SMUD (Sacramento) Fast SAE and Chademo. They charge only 20 cents / kWh and still make 100% profit on electricity. (about $2) I was not required to join "green lots," but the guy on the phone was so kind that I will probably appear as similar to Chargepoint and offer reasonable prices. The security guard is very nice and would "not really notice" that a non-employee in the L2 loading bay (20 + chargers / spots) is mostly empty! There is also an L2 port on the east side of the visitor booth, but it is often used by EV staff for first-class parking.

Possibly the strangest charging site I've ever been to.  These are old (2009) Chargepoint stations with Level 1 only; there are no Level 2 cords.  This hotel was built just last year so they must have inherited these EVSEs from somewhere or got them at an extreme discount.  With Level 1 only, you'll be charging very slow, but it works.

The valet who showed me the stations said they had been there since the hotel opened about a year ago.  I had pestered this hotel about putting in EVSEs during construction last year but never heard anything back.  The valet said he'd seen several cars use it.

Besides this location, there are a couple other hotels in Atlanta that also offer charging, including the Loews in Midtown and the Sheraton downtown.
augmented: Perhaps the strangest charging station I have ever visited. These are old (2009) charging stations with only Level 1; there are no Level 2 cables. The valet who showed me the stations said they have been there since the hotel opened about a year ago. I had harassed this hotel during the construction last year about the use of EVSEs, but never heard anything. original: Have an expired evGo card but had to call toll-free number. Support person helpful, was able to start charging ASAP. However, the price for a one-time charge is significantly higher than other providers. $9.95 for 30 minutes which took me to 10 bars from 3 bars. Other providers such as Blink and Charge Point charge less or offer a better subscription plan for lower rates. Blink membership is free or low cost and offers $1 per hour L2 charging and $2 per hour non-member. L3 charging for members is approximately $5-8, depending on location, for members. Charge Point is comparably priced, depending on location. While it was handy having this DCQC, I'll avoid it in the future if possible as a poor value for approximately $3 worth of electricity with a $6.95 "convenience charge" for QC. I don't like their subscription model as it's more expensive than others...
augmented: However, the price for a one-time fee is significantly higher than other providers. $9.95 for 30 minutes, which took me to 10 bars out of 3 bars. Other providers such as Blink and Charge Point charge less or offer a better subscription rate for lower prices. Blink membership is free or cheap and offers $1 per hour L2 top-up and $2 per hour non-member. L3 top-up for members is about $5-8, depending on location, for members. Charge Point is comparably expensive depending on location. Although it was convenient to have this DCQC, I will avoid it in the future, if possible, as a bad value for electricity worth about $3 with a "convenience fee" of $6.95 for QC. I don't like their subscription model as it is more expensive than others...

original:
Joel,  If you haven't been watching the EV Fast Charger prices, I can understand your reaction to our price.  Here is a sample of our Fast Charging competition.  The Blink network charges $0.65/kWh ($0.59 for members) and eVgo, charges $4.95 + $0.20/minute or >$10 for a 30 minute charge.  The average fast charge at our site is about 10 kWh, which would be $8.90 for a charge of about 30 minutes.  Both Blink and eVgo networks were built on government grants with equipment not meant for a coastal environment.  

As for usage, we did not see a dramatic increase in usage when technical problems caused us to offer fast charging for free this summer and we have not seen a dramatic decrease in usage now that we have resumed charging for the power.

We are constrained by our costs.  Commercial power costs $0.24/kWh and we risk a $3.00/kWh demand charge if the fast charger causes us to exceed peak demand.  We also have network, insurance, security, rent and the installation costs.  The fast charger costs 6-7 times what the 220v charger costs, which means a higher price to use.
  
So, we're not going to offer fast charging at the same price as 220v charging, instead we offer drivers a choice.  You can balance the extra hour charging time versus the extra $5.00 for 10kWh.  The important thing is that an area of California that was not conveniently accessible to EVs now is.  We have customers using both chargers and we welcome everyone.

Sincerely,
Richard Sachen
Sunspeed Enterprises
augmented: Joel, If you haven't been watching the prices of the EV fast charger, I can understand your reaction to our price. Here's an example of our fast charger competition. The Blink network charges $0.65 / kWh ($0.59 for members) and eVgo charges $4.95 + $0.20 / minute or & gt; $10 for a 30-minute charge. Average fast charging at our site is about 10 kWh, which would be $8.90 for a charge of about 30 minutes. Both Blink and eVgo networks have been built on government subsidies with equipment not intended for a coastal environment. In terms of consumption, we haven't seen a dramatic increase in consumption when technical problems prompted us to offer fast charging for free this summer, and we haven't seen a dramatic drop in consumption now that we've resumed charging for electricity. We're constrained by our costs. Commercial electricity costs $0.24 / kWh, and we risk a $3.00 charge when the fast charger causes us to peak demand.

original:
Nissan NCTC

2015-05-10
Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps under their current design should have separate listings for L3s so that status (like under repair) and alerts (like all stations in use and station has become available) make sense for real human EV users.    
                                                 Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are failing to be honest in several ways:

0. Many stations are out of order, but not listed as such on the advertising posters in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for under repair. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of order but still using the normally working icon.

1. They do not provide 30-minute free sessions.

2. They fail to time the sessions for you.

3. They fail to cut off the session at 30 minutes.

4. If you go over, they charge you $7. This requires you to leave work or whatever you are doing, exactly in time to cut it off. If you leave too early, then you cut your session short. If you leave right on time, you must still cut your session a little short to avoid going over the 30 minutes on your own timing.

5. They refuse to document or provide measures for when the timer starts and when it ends.

6. When touch screens do not work, you cannot use NCTC over app or telephone. They say you can dispute it later, but their dispute process is opaque and time consuming. That is not a free 30-minute charge, either.

7. What they should have done, and what they probably originally meant to do, is simply provide $7 fast charges for free to NCTC customers.
augmented: Nissan NCTC2015-05-10Plugshare and EZ-Charge apps in their current design should have separate listings for L3s, so status (as in repair) and alarms (as in all stations that are in use and station has become available) make sense for real human users of electric vehicles. Nissan advertises 30 minutes free with NCTC on L3s. Unfortunately, they are not honest in several respects: 0. Many stations are out of service, but not listed as such on the billboards in Nissan dealerships or in the EZ-Charge app, which has a special icon for repairs. In Phoenix, about 5 of 21 stations are currently out of service, but still use the normally functioning tool.1. They do not offer 30-minute free sittings.2. They fail to schedule the sessions for you.3. They do not interrupt the session after 30 minutes.4. If you pass, they charge you $7. This requires you to stop work or whatever you do just in time to exit them.
